The content in this package aims for representing the content of table 28 (17) in DIS19109:2025 in UML. It is supposed to show 19109 native elements and re-used and or derived elements from 19103 in a conceptually correct way. However, this model may come with technically insufficient information in order to export the profile and/or generate MDG technology, which again can be imported by users of Enterprise Architect. For this reason an additional profile ("ISO19103merged") has been created.

feature attribute characteristic of a feature
NOTE: A feature attribute has a name, a data type, and a value domain associated to it. A feature attribute for a feature instance also has an attribute value taken from the value domain. EXAMPLE: A feature attribute named 'color' may have an attribute value 'green' which belongs to the data type 'text'. A feature attribute named 'length' may have an attribute value '82.4' which belongs to the data type 'real'. [Victoria Terminology Harmonization Meeting]

represents attributes which carry a spatial reference to a feature by using a geographic identifier, having Location as value type. Ideally that GeographicIdentifier is scoped (e.g., is in a namespace) to a gazetteer
represents a spatial attribute, which is used to express spatial characteristics of a feature type. A spatial attribute type has a spatial type or Geometry or a Topology as value type

represents attributes that carry metadata information when such information is included as data in a dataset. This has MD_Metadata as value type. These attribute types may use the metadata element interfaces defined in the Metadata Schema (ISO 19115 1) as their value types
IdentifiedType is a metaclass from which the other key classes in the General Feature Model inherit some common identification and description attributes.
description of a constraint made on the IdentifiedType or specified on properties within a type

representation of the element by an expression that describes it and differentiates it from other elements. One definition is mandatory. Additional definitions can be provided in multiple languages if required

representation for the element by a sign which denotes it in a domain or subject
a machine-readable name of the element, which is same in all languages that the schema is documented in
represents thematic attributes whose value varies as a function of spatio-temporal position within the scope of a feature

the class for a relationship between a more general feature type (supertype) and one specialized feature type (subtype). Any instance of a specialized feature type is also an instance of the general feature type

a Boolean variable, where TRUE means that an instance of the supertype shall not be an instance of more than one of the subtypes, whereas FALSE means that an instance of the supertype may be an instance of more than one subtype. Optional with a default value of true
represents temporal associations that may exist between features
the abstract superclass for AttributeType and FeatureAssociationRole, which provide characteristics that may be associated with a feature type

number of instances of non-abstract subtypes of PropertyType
For the subtype AttributeType this is the number of instances of the attribute that may be associated with a single instance of a feature type
For the subtype FeatureAssociationRole this is the number of instances of the feature type that can act in this role relative to a single instance of the feature type at the other end of the association
data type of the attribute value or the role value
association role to specify a certain feature type which is an instance class of the FeatureType metaclass

association role to specify any feature attribute type and any feature association role that carries characteristics of a feature type. While strictly optional, it is unlikely for a feature type to be defined having no properties
represents attributes that carry quality information. These attributes are used when a quality characteristic of a feature or its properties is included as data in the dataset
represents spatial relationships or topological relationships that may exist between features. Those relationships depend upon the relative spatial position and extent of features

The operation evaluate shall accept a DirectPosition as input and return the record of attribute values for that direct position. The data type Record is defined in ISO 19103. If the direct position passed is not in the spatiotemporal domain, then an error message shall be generated

The operation "evaluateInverse" shall accept a Record of values as input and return a set of CV_DomainObjects. Normally, this will be the set of CV_DomainObjects in the Domain that are associated with values equal to those in the input Record. However, the operation may return other CV_DomainObjects derived from those in the Domain, as specified by the application schema.
